        "theme":  "Philosophy",
        "summary":  "CIO Thornton May argues that deploying AI and technology systems alone is insufficient without investing in stakeholder education and organizational comprehension. He introduces the concept of knowledge pumping ΓÇö actively building narratives and understanding around technology so users can extract full value rather than assuming robust tools will work regardless of user capability. The piece warns against over-engineering systems to compensate for lack of user understanding.",
        "execSummary":  "This is a direct challenge to the popular instinct of locking down AI tools to prevent misuse: May argues that user education, not system restriction, is the sustainable path to AI value realization. For customer-support leaders deploying AI agents, this means investing in agent training and change management alongside the technology itself ΓÇö without user comprehension, even well-designed AI tools underperform. The knowledge pumping framework is a useful lens for evaluating AI adoption programs. The caveat is that education initiatives require sustained investment and executive sponsorship, which are often the first cuts when budgets tighten.",
