        "summary":  "Princeton and University of Chicago researchers placed large language models in simulated hiring scenarios and found they demonstrated significantly stronger stereotyping behavior than human participants, with newer reasoning-capable models showing the most pronounced biases. LLMs quickly segregated candidates by ethnicity into job categories when given limited information, though reduced their discriminatory patterns when provided relevant personal qualification details. Researchers found that incorporating diversity incentives into AI decision-making goals substantially reduced bias formation, while simply instructing models to be fair proved ineffective.",
